Question_1.Context: The study aimed to identify the effect of material type and process parameters on the mechanical properties of 3D printed long-fibre reinforced polymer composites.
Question_1.Question: Which reinforcement type offered the largest increase in both Ultimate Tensile Strength (UTS) and Flexural Modulus for Onyx material?
Question_1.Source: For Onyx, carbon fibre reinforcement offered the largest increase in both UTS and Flexural Modulus over unreinforced material.

Question_2.Context: The study investigated the effect of matrix material, reinforcement type, volume of reinforcement, and reinforcement lay-up orientation on UTS and Flexural Modulus.
Question_2.Question: Which parameter had the largest impact on both UTS and Flexural Strength?
Question_2.Source: Statistical analysis indicated that changing the number of layers of reinforcement had the largest impact on both UTS and Flexural Strength.

Question_3.Context: The study focused on the mechanical performance of two common matrix materials employed in Material Extrusion with a range of fibre reinforcements.
Question_3.Question: Which reinforcement material showed the highest increase in Flexural Modulus over Nylon material?
Question_3.Source: Similarly, for Nylon, the UTS and Flexural Modulus were increased by 1431 ± 56% and 1924 ± 5% by the addition of carbon fibre reinforcement.

Question_4.Context: The study analyzed the mechanical properties of different composite components manufactured using a Material Extrusion process.
Question_4.Question: Which parameter had a minor effect on the mechanical properties of the composites?
Question_4.Source: 'Fibre orientation' within the bounds of these trials had very little impact on either UTS or E.

Question_5.Context: The study evaluated the cost to strength ratio for different composite materials.
Question_5.Question: Which composite material achieved the lowest cost to strength ratio for Ultimate Tensile Strength (UTS)?
Question_5.A: GF reinforced Nylon with 12 layers and (0,90) lay-up
Question_5.B: CF reinforced Onyx with 12 layers and (0,90) lay-up
Question_5.C: KF reinforced Nylon with 12 layers and (0,45) lay-up
Question_5.D: CF reinforced Onyx with 12 layers and (0,45) lay-up
Question_5.Source: The lowest cost to strength ratio (most desirable) is achieved using a GF reinforced Nylon with 12 layers and (0,90) lay-up.

Question_6.Context: The study compared the experimental values for UTS and E against the calculated values for different composite materials.
Question_6.Question: Which composite material achieved the highest Ultimate Tensile Strength (UTS) compared to the calculated value?
Question_6.A: CF reinforced Onyx with 12 layers and (0,90) lay-up
Question_6.B: GF reinforced Nylon with 12 layers and (0,90) lay-up
Question_6.C: KF reinforced Nylon with 12 layers and (0,45) lay-up
Question_6.D: KF reinforced Onyx with 12 layers and (0,90) lay-up
Question_6.Source: The highest UTS (278 ± 8 MPa) and stiffest material is CF reinforced Onyx with 12 layers and (0,90).

Question_7.Question: Which parameter was found to have a minor effect on determining both tensile and flexural properties?
